# 💡 Smart Lighting System using STM32 (LDR + IR + LED)

## 📌 Overview

This project implements a **smart lighting system** using an LDR (Light Dependent Resistor) and an IR sensor with an STM32 microcontroller. The system intelligently controls an LED based on ambient light conditions and object detection, ensuring energy-efficient operation.

---

## 🎯 Features

* Automatic lighting based on ambient light
* Motion/object detection using IR sensor
* Energy-efficient operation (dual-condition control)
* Real-time embedded decision logic
* Simple and reliable implementation

---

## 🧠 Working Principle

The system reads ambient light intensity using an LDR connected to the ADC and detects object presence using an IR sensor (digital input).

The LED turns ON **only when both conditions are satisfied**:

* Environment is **dark**
* Motion/object is **detected**

Otherwise, the LED remains OFF.

---

## 🔧 Hardware Used

* STM32 (e.g., STM32F446RE / Nucleo board)
* LDR sensor (onboard or external)
* IR sensor module
* LED

---

## 🔌 Pin Configuration

| Peripheral | Pin  |
| ---------- | ---- |
| LDR (ADC)  | PA0  |
| IR Sensor  | PB10 |
| LED        | PB3  |

---

## ⚙️ Software Configuration

* IDE: STM32CubeIDE
* Language: C (HAL Drivers)
* ADC Resolution: 12-bit
* GPIO:

  * Input (IR sensor) with pull-down
  * Output (LED)

---

## 🔄 System Logic

```id="q5g7ln"
IF (Dark AND Motion Detected)
    LED = ON
ELSE
    LED = OFF
```

---

## 📊 Threshold Setting

```id="yzgk9v"
#define THRESHOLD 2000
```

* Adjust this value based on your lighting conditions
* Lower value → more sensitive to darkness

---

## ▶️ How to Run

1. Open project in STM32CubeIDE
2. Build and flash the code
3. Place system in different lighting conditions
4. Trigger IR sensor and observe LED behavior

---

## ⚠️ Notes

* Ensure correct IR sensor logic (HIGH/LOW may vary by module)
* Calibrate LDR threshold for accurate detection
* Onboard LDR may have inverted response (adjust logic if needed)

---

